This paper deals with the problem of learning a similarity metric from human annotated data, which is a common problem in machine learning and falls under the category of "Learning" (cs.LG). The paper specifically focuses on the COMPAS dataset, which is used for criminal recidivism prediction, and discusses the notion of individual fairness, which is a topic of interest in the field of "Cybersecurity and Privacy" (cs.CY). The paper also evaluates the performance of several metric learning methods, which is a common topic in the sub-category of "Cryptography and Security" (cs.CR). The paper uses human supervision to learn the similarity metric, which is a common approach in the field of "Artificial Intelligence" (cs.AI). Finally, the paper discusses the implications of its findings for understanding human supervision, which is a topic of interest in the sub-category of "Social and Information Networks" (cs.SI).
